Solution. From the inequality between the arithmetic and geometric mean, we get $a^{2}+1 \geq 2 a$, so $\frac{a}{a^{2}+1} \leq \frac{1}{2}$, i.e., $-\frac{a}{a^{2}+1} \geq-\frac{1}{2}$. Similarly, $-\frac{b}{b^{2}+1} \geq-\frac{1}{2}$ and $-\frac{c}{c^{2}+1} \geq-\frac{1}{2}$. Now, we transform the left side of the given inequality and if we use the last three inequalities, we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{a^{3}}{a^{2}+1}+\frac{b^{3}}{b^{2}+1}+\frac{c^{3}}{c^{2}+1} & =\frac{a^{3}+a-a}{a^{2}+1}+\frac{b^{3}+b-b}{b^{2}+1}+\frac{c^{3}+c-c}{c^{2}+1} \\
& =a-\frac{a}{a^{2}+1}+b-\frac{b}{b^{2}+1}+c-\frac{c}{c^{2}+1} \\
& =3-\frac{a}{a^{2}+1}-\frac{b}{b^{2}+1}-\frac{c}{c^{2}+1} \\
& \geq 3-\frac{3}{2}=\frac{3}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

which is what we needed to prove.

