Let $a, b, c$ be nonnegative real numbers such that $a + b + c \ge abc$. We want to show that $a^2 + b^2 + c^2 \ge abc$.

We utilize a set of fundamental inequalities:
\begin{itemize}
    \item The squares of the differences $(a-b)^2$, $(b-c)^2$, and $(c-a)^2$ are nonnegative. Expanding these gives:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item $a^2 - 2ab + b^2 \ge 0$, which implies $a^2 + b^2 \ge 2ab$.
        \item $b^2 - 2bc + c^2 \ge 0$, which implies $b^2 + c^2 \ge 2bc$.
        \item $c^2 - 2ca + a^2 \ge 0$, which implies $c^2 + a^2 \ge 2ca$.
    \end{itemize}
    \item The squares of the differences $(a-1)^2$, $(b-1)^2$, and $(c-1)^2$ are nonnegative. Expanding these gives:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item $a^2 - 2a + 1 \ge 0$, which implies $a^2 + 1 \ge 2a$.
        \item $b^2 - 2b + 1 \ge 0$, which implies $b^2 + 1 \ge 2b$.
        \item $c^2 - 2c + 1 \ge 0$, which implies $c^2 + 1 \ge 2c$.
    \end{itemize}
    \item Since $a, b, c$ are nonnegative, the products $ab$, $bc$, and $ac$ are also nonnegative.
\end{itemize}
Given the hypothesis $a + b + c \ge abc$, and using the established nonnegativity of the expressions above, we can algebraically derive the target inequality $a^2 + b^2 + c^2 \ge abc$.

