informal_proof:
The problem asks us to count the number of integers \(x\) such that \(x\) is strictly greater than \(-\pi\) and \(x\) is not a natural number.

First, let's analyze the condition \(x > -\pi\). We know that the value of \(\pi\) is approximately 3.14159. Therefore, \(-\pi\) is approximately -3.14159. Since \(x\) must be an integer, the condition \(x > -\pi\) is equivalent to stating that \(x\) must be greater than or equal to the smallest integer that is strictly greater than \(-\pi\). This integer is \(-3\). Thus, the first condition implies \(x \geq -3\).

Next, let's analyze the condition that \(x\) is not a natural number. The set of natural numbers, \(\mathbb{N}\), is typically considered to be \(\{0, 1, 2, 3, \ldots\}\). So, if \(x\) is not a natural number, it must be a negative integer. This means \(x \in \{\ldots, -3, -2, -1\}\).

Now we combine these two conditions. We are looking for integers \(x\) such that \(x \geq -3\) and \(x\) is a negative integer.
The integers satisfying \(x \geq -3\) are \(-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, \ldots\).
From this set, we must select only the negative integers. This yields the set \(\{-3, -2, -1\}\).

We verify that each element in this set satisfies the original conditions:
\begin{itemize}
    \item For \(x = -3\):
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \( -3 > -\pi \): This is true because \(\pi > 3\), so \(-\pi < -3\).
        \item \( \neg \exists n : \mathbb{N}, -3 = n \): This is true because \(-3\) is negative and natural numbers are non-negative.
    \end{itemize}
    \item For \(x = -2\):
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \( -2 > -\pi \): This is true because \(\pi > 3\), so \(-\pi < -3\), which implies \(-\pi < -2\).
        \item \( \neg \exists n : \mathbb{N}, -2 = n \): This is true because \(-2\) is negative.
    \end{itemize}
    \item For \(x = -1\):
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \( -1 > -\pi \): This is true because \(\pi > 3\), so \(-\pi < -3\), which implies \(-\pi < -1\).
        \item \( \neg \exists n : \mathbb{N}, -1 = n \): This is true because \(-1\) is negative.
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
All integers in the set \(\{-3, -2, -1\}\) satisfy both given conditions. Furthermore, any integer satisfying the conditions must be in this set. Thus, the set of integers we are interested in is precisely \(\{-3, -2, -1\}\).

The number of elements in this set is 3.

